1.1 We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical inventory of PPE annually to prove its existence, determine the condition and update the valuation thru the following procedures:

Physically count all existing PPE and provide its description.  Secure other information such as person accountable/user, date of purchase, brand, model, serial no., engine no., etc. and determine if unserviceable or not;

Based on the information gathered in procedure no. 1 determine if there are accounting records for these PPEs.  Prepare a PPELC for each PPE with accounting records or data, identify and determine its total cost and compute a separate depreciation schedule. PPE without accounting records should be properly disclosed;

Identify the accountable employee for each PPE and issue a Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR)/Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE);

For the current purchases of PPE, immediately prepare a PPELC and issue a PAR/ARE to the employee;

Identify the employee responsible for the PPEs which no longer exist or not presented and require the submission of an explanation and/or request for relief; and

The Municipal Accountant should make necessary adjusting entries to remove from the books PPEs which are unserviceable and were properly disposed.

4.1 We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Direct the full implementation of the provisions of RA No. 9003 especially on the establishment of sanitary landfill or any other acceptable/authorized alternative types of dumpsite;

Fast track the documents for the donation of land where the dumpsite is located;

Improve/rehabilitate the road that leads to the dumpsite for easy access of vehicles at all times;

Purchase additional equipment for the collection and disposal of the solid wastes; and

Follow up the enactment of a Municipal Ordinance that will efficiently and effectively implement the solid waste management system by applying the following:

Impose a thorough collection of garbage based on set schedules for all barangays of the Municipality;

Require the strict implementation of waste segregation;

Organize Information, Education and Communication (IEC) campaign on proper waste segregation and disposal to the community; 

Issue protective equipment to the garbage collectors; and

Install other efficient and effective ways necessary to address the problem on garbage collection, segregation and disposal of the Municipality.

5.1 We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Instruct the persons concerned to immediately look into the unimplemented development projects under the 20% Development Fund and determine causes of non-implementation;

Formulate/develop specific strategies/solutions to effectively implement development projects;

Consider formulating a timetable within which to complete the unimplemented projects and review the costing of projects programmed to conform to the present conditions; and

Review the agreement between the Contractor and Municipality and make necessary actions in order to compel the completion of the projects which are still in the “Construction in Progress” account for a long period of time.

8.1 We recommended that:

The Municipal Accountant make necessary adjusting entries to set up the receivable account and close the inventory account;

The Project Management Team (PMT) of the programs exert efforts to collect the amount from the beneficiaries through the following:

Send demand letters informing them of their obligations;
Conduct ocular inspections and monitoring of the beneficiaries to determine the reasons for non-payment; and
Based on the results of procedure “b”, develop a plan in order for the beneficiaries to pay their obligations.

9.1 We recommended the following:

The Local Chief Executive and Municipal Accountant demand the liquidation or refund of the cash advances and deduct from their salaries if no action was taken by the accountable officer;

The OIC- Municipal Treasurer request the Municipal Mayor to direct the refund and inform the employers of those who transferred to other government agencies of the unliquidated cash advances; 

The Municipal Accountant identify the specific cash advances of the OIC-Municipal Treasurer that were over liquidated and make necessary adjustments;

The LGU shall follow the guidelines and procedures set in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 on the write-off of the unliquidated cash advances which have been long outstanding/remained dormant in the books; and

The Municipal Officials and Employees strictly observe the pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 and other relevant laws, rules and regulations on cash advances.

10.1 We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the concerned employees to strictly follow the guidelines prescribed by COA Circular No. 96-010 and install, implement and monitor a sound system of internal control by performing the following:

The canvasser shall instruct the supplier or its representative that the quotation shall not exceed the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC) as indicated in the PR to avail the most advantageous price for the government;

Properly date and number the POs for systematic monitoring of purchased transactions;

State delivery terms and conditions for clarity of agreement between the parties;

Provide all other requirements of the aforementioned Circular; and

Adopt appropriate internal control measures by reviewing thoroughly the documents and check completeness and accuracy of information prior to approval of transactions.

